SIMPLE: poach
RECORDS: 4

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Poach
<hw>Poach</hw> <pr>(p⟦omac⟧ch)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp.
& p. p.</pos> <conjf>Poached</conjf> <pr>(p⟦omac⟧cht)</pr>; <pos>p. pr.
& vb. n.</pos> <conjf>Poaching</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[F.
<ets>pocher</ets> to place in a pocket, to poach eggs (the yolk of the
egg being as it were <ets>pouched</ets> in the white), from
<ets>poche</ets> pocket, pouch. See <er>Pouch</er>, <pos>v. &
n.</pos>]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To cook, as eggs, by breaking them into
boiling water; also, to cook with butter after breaking in a
vessel.</def> <rj><au>Bacon.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To rob of game; to pocket and convey away by
stealth, as game; hence, to plunder.</def> <rj><au>Garth.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Poach</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Poach
<hw>Poach</hw>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <def>To steal or pocket game, or to
carry it away privately, as in a bag; to kill or destroy game contrary
to law, especially by night; to hunt or fish unlawfully; <as>as, to
<ex>poach</ex> for rabbits or for salmon</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Poach</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Poach
<hw>Poach</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <ety>[Cf. OF. <ets>pocher</ets> to
thrust or dig out with the fingers, to bruise (the eyes), F.
<ets>pouce</ets> thumb, L. <ets>pollex</ets>, and also E.
<ets>poach</ets> to cook eggs, to plunder, and <ets>poke</ets> to thrust
against.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To stab; to pierce; to spear, as
fish.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark> <rj><au>Carew.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To force, drive, or plunge into anything.</def>
<mark>[Obs.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>His horse <qex>poching</qex> one of his legs into some hollow
ground.</q> <rj><qau>Sir W. Temple.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>To make soft or muddy by trampling.</def>
<rj><au>Tennyson.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>To begin and not complete.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>
<rj><au>Bacon.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Poach</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 4 ====
HEADWORD: Poach
<hw>Poach</hw>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <def>To become soft or muddy.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Chalky and clay lands . . . chap in summer, and <qex>poach</qex>
in winter.</q> <rj><qau>Mortimer.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Poachard</ent>⟦br⟧
